The costs of these provisions are offset by taxes, fees, and cost-saving measures, such as new Medicare taxes for those in high-income brackets, taxes on indoor tanning, cuts to the Medicare Advantage program in favor of traditional Medicare, and fees on medical devices and pharmaceutical companies;[327] there is also a tax penalty for those who do not obtain health insurance, unless they are exempt due to low income or other reasons.[328] In March 2010, the CBO estimated that the net effect of both laws will be a reduction in the federal deficit by $143Â billion over the first decade.[329]
